In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims March 2015 as National Colorectal Cancer Awareness Month. He highlights the significance of raising awareness about colorectal cancer, which is the second leading cause of cancer deaths in the United States. The President emphasizes the importance of early detection and treatment, as well as regular screenings for individuals between the ages of 50 and 75. He encourages Americans to learn more about the risk factors and symptoms of colorectal cancer. President Obama also mentions the Affordable Care Act, which provides more families with access to quality and affordable healthcare, including coverage for recommended preventive services like colorectal cancer screenings. He further discusses the Precision Medicine Initiative, aimed at designing and testing tailored treatments for individual patients. The President concludes by honoring those who have been affected by colorectal cancer and calling for continued efforts in research, advocacy, and quality care to fight against cancer.